<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Regulator move lifts generators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and CLARE GASCOIGNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Relief lifted the two English power generators above the sliding market
trend following the decision by Offer, the industry regulator, not to refer
the companies to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. PowerGen shares
surged 16 to 541p with 7.8m traded, while National Power put on 14 1/2 to
475 1/2 p with turnover hitting a hefty 21m.
The market was almost unanimous in its view that the two companies - which
had faced a potentially damaging MMC referral over pool pricing - had come
out of the situation well. Analysts said that even the divestments of power
stations demanded by the regulator could easily be met from the companies'
spare capacity. The pool price cap was also seen as undemanding.
With regulatory worries now removed, the shares are forecast to make further
gains. Hoare Govett sees a 10 per cent upside in the near term, and further
strengthening should the government decide to sell its remaining 40 per cent
holdings. Analysts said strong dividend growth over the next three years
would also underpin support.
The regional electricity companies (Recs) continued weak as investors shied
away in response to the view from some in the market that the shares were
overbought.
There was also talk that one US house had a large seller, prompted by the
improving US bond market. Eastern, which retreated 6 to 678p, announced
after the market had closed that it had bought a further 750,000 of its
shares at prices ranging from 676p to 678p.
</TEXT>
