<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Markets Report: Pressure on Dollars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investor support for the dollar weakened yesterday following the release of
weak sales and inflation data and uncertainty surrounding trade talks with
Japan, writes Philip Gawith.
Market attention was focused on the Washington summit between President
Clinton and Mr Morihiro Hosokawa. Trade was initially directionless, but the
dollar started to slide when pessimism set in about the talks. It closed in
London at Y107.9 against Y108.450 on Thursday.
Sterling finished the week slightly stronger after earlier falling more than
5 pfennigs in a negative response to Tuesday's 25 basis point cut in
interest rates. It closed in London at DM2.5685, up from DM2.5625 on
Thursday.
The dollar lost ground against the D-Mark as the release of weak data
combined with scepticism about the likelihood of a Bundesbank rate-cut on
Thursday. It closed in London at DM1.7517, marginally down on Thursday's
close of DM1.7534.
Seasonally adjusted total retail sales fell by 0.5 per cent compared to a
forecast increase of 0.4 per cent. January producer prices rose by 0.2 per
cent, lower than the 0.4 per cent gain forecast. The market sold the dollar
reasoning that these figures made a further tightening in US policy more
distant.
Analysts cautioned against reading too much into the figures which were
distorted by bad weather and an earthquake.
Against the yen, meanwhile, the succinct view of one observer was that 'most
people don't have a clue where the rate is going.' The tenor of comments
emerging from US and Japanese officials was not encouraging. Late yesterday
US Commerce Secretary Mr Ron Brown told a TV station that the trade talks
were not going well. 'We are very disappointed. They (the negotiations)
still don't look good.'
Earlier the yen rose against the dollar after a senior US official refused
to rule out retaliation if the talks failed. 'We want a good agreement or no
agreement. We won't settle for anything less,' the official was quoted as
saying. Earlier comments from US vice-president Al Gore also had an air of
preemptive damage limitation about them.
Mr Clinton and Mr Hosokawa sought agreements which offered cheaper foreign
goods to Japanese consumers and new export opportunities for US companies.
Some observers took comfort from the fact that both leaders have reputations
as dealmakers. Mr Paul Lambert, currency economist at UBS, said if a deal
emerged, attention would shift towards economic fundamentals which favoured
a stronger dollar. The recent strength of the yen has been largely a
function of political considerations, although foreign buying of equities
has also helped the currency.
Sterling fell below DM2.56 and Dollars 1.46 on news of a higher than
expected trade gap with the rest of world in November. It later recovered to
finish the day half a cent higher at Dollars 1.4663.
The D-Mark was firmer across the board in late European trade with the
prospect of a Bundesbank rate cut on Thursday increasingly discounted. It
closed at Ffr3.40 and L965.3 respectively against the French and Italian
currencies, marginally stronger in both cases.
The Bank of England provided the UK money market with Pounds 950m of
assistance in line with its revised forecast for the day.
</TEXT>
