<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / International Company News: Cap Gemini seeks funds as losses
mount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Cap Gemini Sogeti, the French computer services group, yesterday announced
increased net losses of FFr434m (Dollars 72.9m) for last year. It plans to
raise FFr1.5bn in new capital.
The results for 1993, which the group described as provisional, compare with
net losses of FFr333m the previous year, excluding exceptional capital gains
of FFr261m from the sale of a property near the Arc de Triomphe in Paris.
Sales in 1993 fell 7.4 per cent to FFr11bn.
The company forecast a gradual improvement in its performance. It was
looking forward to 'less difficult market conditions' and the impact of its
Genesis programme, involving a radical restructuring of the group's
operations and activities.
The programme, launched in 1992, is aimed at establishing a more efficient
system of management across the group's various geographical and business
activities. Under the new system, so-called 'strategic business areas' are
organised along both geographical and industry sector lines, allowing
different regions to specialise in the sector where they are strongest. The
group's US operation, for example, is the centre for the oil and gas
division.
Cap Gemini spelt out a further reorganisation of the group in 1994. It said
it would extend its programme of selling non-core assets, following the
disposal of its stakes in Sweden's Jacobson &amp; Widmark AB and Carelcomp of
Finland. In Germany, the company planned to integrate CAP Debis with Debis
Systemhaus, a subsidiary of Daimler Benz, which holds 51 per cent of CAP
Debis.
'The merger will reinforce the co-operation with Debis and create a company
with sales of FFr6bn and a complete range of services,' the company said.
The increase in capital, aimed at strengthening the group's balance sheet
and reducing financial costs, will be largely supported by Sogeti, the
principal shareholder in CGS. The company said Sogeti should participate in
the capital injection in line with its 61.5 per cent stake in CGS.
Details of the capital increase have yet to be finalised.
</TEXT>
