<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: UK government stand on biodiesel hits
farmers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ALASTER M FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, You published two interesting articles, 'Trees branch out', about
coppicing on set-aside land for energy uses, and 'The cleaner choice', about
concerns on particulate emissions from diesel engines (both Business and the
Environment, February 9).
We would like to point out that the use of biodiesel (made from rape seed
oil) has been shown to reduce particular emissions from diesel engines by up
to 50 per cent. In 1994, about 250,000ha of set-aside land will be used to
grow oil crops for biodiesel production and the potential is much larger.
In France, Italy and Germany, tax exemption is given (under certain control
systems) to promote the use of biodiesel and hence the development of the
set-aside policy.
Unfortunately, the UK government has to date refused to apply the same
scheme, to the detriment of UK farmers, diesel users and the environment.
Alaster M Fraser,
market development manager,
Novamont SpA,
Milan, Italy
</TEXT>
