<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Kent Tec merger dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A proposed merger of Kent County Council's economic development unit and the
local Training and Enterprise Council has been abandoned.
Councillors, officers and Tec directors will instead set up a joint policy
group to 'identify and explore opportunities for closer executive action'.
The merger plan, which was strongly supported by Sir Alastair Morton,
co-chairman of Eurotunnel and chairman of Kent Tec, had been seen by local
authorities and Tecs as an important test of how obstacles to closer
partnerships between the public and private sectors could be overcome.
The proposed merger would have created one strategic body responsible for
writing Kent's economic development plan as well as promoting regeneration
projects and inward investment.
One issue involved in the collapse of talks was the question of how
councillors could continue to contribute to the strategy for local economic
development.
