<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Foreigners hold 12% of shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Overseas investors held about 12 per cent, or Pounds 75bn, of all UK shares
at the end of 1992, figures from the Central Statistical Office showed
yesterday.
US investors accounted for just under half of the overseas total, at Pounds
36bn, while the Japanese represented 2.7 per cent. Continental Europeans
were the second largest overseas shareholders, owning about 17.5 per cent,
or Pounds 13bn, followed by Opec investors, with 6.4 per cent, about Pounds
5bn.
The figures appear in the CSO's annual share register survey, which includes
investors' countries of residence for the first time. The figures are
subject to uncertainty because the CSO was unable to allocate about Pounds
15bn of overseas holdings to particular areas.
UK financial institutions held the largest proportion, 56.6 per cent, or
Pounds 351bn, of UK shares. Among the institutions, pension funds were
dominant, with around Pounds 215bn - or a third of all shares - and
insurance companies with Pounds 103bn, about a sixth. Individuals owned 20.3
per cent.
The survey revealed that about 23,000 holdings, worth between Pounds 10m and
Pounds 50m, were held by individuals in the Channel Islands and the Isle of
Man. Registers of 191 companies were covered by the survey, representing
about 79 per cent of the capitalisation of UK companies' ordinary shares
listed on the International Stock Exchange in London.
</TEXT>
