<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / MPs support ban on tobacco advertising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Legislation to ban tobacco advertising crossed a tough hurdle yesterday
after a private member's bill gained the support in the Commons of more than
a third of MPs.
The tobacco advertising bill, proposed by Mr Kevin Barron, backbench Labour
MP for Rother Valley, passed its second reading in spite of strong
opposition from a number of government ministers.
The bill will now be debated by a parliamentary committee at which
ministerial opposition will almost certainly be stepped up.
The scale of support for the legislation on both sides of the house took the
government by surprise. In a free vote, a motion to close the day's debate
and push the bill to its next stage was passed by 227 votes to 17, a
majority of 210.
Under Commons rules, the Friday debate on a private member's bill must be
formally closed by the early afternoon if it is to make any more progress.
It must also be supported by more than 100 MPs - difficult to muster on a
Friday afternoon when members tend to be in their constituencies.
Mr Barron claimed yesterday that it was almost unprecedented for the
division on a Friday debate to be so well attended. 'It shows the concern
(MPs) have over the influence tobacco advertising has on the health of
children in the UK,' he said.
In recent months, the legislation appears to have gained support from
influential circles - overcoming opposition from the powerful tobacco
industry.
A leaked cabinet memorandum recently showed that three ministers - including
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary - urged in November that
the ban should be supported.
They opposed Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, who told the
cabinet that she backed extending the limitations on advertising, including
adverts on posters, shop-fronts and women's magazines.
</TEXT>
