<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / MGN pension case dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Capel-Cure Myers, the securities house, has dropped its Pounds 6m legal
action against Credit Suisse arising from CCM's litigation with the Mirror
Group Newspapers pension scheme trustees over the Maxwell affair.
Capel-Cure Myers, one of the fund managers which acted for the MGN pension
scheme, had begun proceedings against Credit Suisse for alleged breach of
trust over the handling of assets it had passed to the bank.
The decision to settle is a direct consequence of last month's out-of-court
settlement of the main litigation when Capel-Cure Myers, Invesco Asset
Management and Lehman Brothers agreed to pay a total of Pounds 32m to the
pension fund trustees. Of this, Capel-Cure Myers paid Pounds 6m, Lehmans
Pounds 15m and Invesco Pounds 11m.
Under the terms of yesterday's settlement, Credit Suisse has continued not
to admit any liability. However, both sides have agreed to fund their own
legal costs.
A joint statement from Capel-Cure Myers and Credit Suisse said:
'Participation in the settlement is a commercial judgment by both parties
who believe this course of action to be in the best interests of their
respective businesses.'
Preliminary High Court hearings had begun earlier this week but were
adjourned whilst the out-of-court talks that led to the settlement were
held.
