<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Japan and US fail to reach accord: Rift casts shadow over
trade ties as Clinton and Hosokawa back 'cooling off' period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US and Japan yesterday failed to resolve disagreements over a plan to
give US goods and services greater access to Japanese markets.
President Bill Clinton, in sombre mood, told a press conference after his
summit with Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the prime minister, the Japanese position
'simply did not meet the standards' agreed in Tokyo last July. 'It is better
to have no agreement than an empty agreement,' he added.
Mr Clinton did not publicly threaten US retaliation against Japan, saying
'we need a period of reflection to assess where we are'. However, senior
administration officials said later there was a 'good-sized menu' of options
the US could now consider. They said US trade relations with Japan had
reached 'a turning point', implying an even tougher US stance in the future.
Mr Clinton noted: 'The rest of our relationship is in good shape, but this
is a serious problem.'
Mr Hosokawa also urged a 'cooling off' period after the intense negotiations
between ministers from both sides finally broke off in the small hours of
yesterday morning.
'Unfortunately, at the very end we were not able to clear the hurdle of
numerical targets, and I regret that very much,' he said.
'Numerical targets,' he went on, 'can acquire a life of their own and turn
into another semiconductor case' - a reference to the two-year-old bilateral
agreement aimed at giving the US a 20 per cent share of the Japanese chip
market. This has recently fallen to just over 18 per cent, threatening new
trade tensions.
The most contentious issue in the so-called 'framework' process, which also
embraces macro-economic policies, was the US demand that Japan open its
domestic market in measurable ways to US exports of telecommunications,
medical equipment, cars and car parts, and insurance services. A White House
official said Mr Hosokawa had offered 'continuing negotiations' on the car
sector, where US sales are tiny.
But Mr Clinton had said this would be pointless without 'a change of
attitude' on the Japanese side and without even 'a possibility' that
agreement could be reached. In the press conference, Mr Clinton disputed at
length the Japanese characterisation of the US position, often described as
'managed trade'.
He said the US was seeking 'objective criteria' by which progress could be
judged and which might encompass exchange rate variables, macro-economic
performance and the price and competitiveness of US products.
Mr Clinton's reference to exchange rates was taken in the foreign exchange
markets as a hint that the US might seek a higher yen. In limited futures
trading for March delivery the dollar fell by about one yen. Initial
reaction in political and business circles was to commend Mr Clinton for not
settling for a cosmetic agreement.
Senator Jay Rockefeller, the West Virginia Democrat, said that ultimately
the Japanese government would have 'no alternative but to open its markets'.
The American Electronic Association supported the administration's
determination to get 'full effective and measurable' access to the Japanese
market. An early test case may come next Tuesday when the US trade
representative is due to comment on complaints from Motorola about its
treatment in the Japanese cellular phone sector.
US rice makes Tokyo debut, Page 4 Editorial Comment, Page 10
</TEXT>
