<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / International Company News: AT&amp;T plans 15,000 job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, the US telecoms group, is to cut
14,000-15,000 jobs, signalling the growing competitive pressures in the
market for long-distance telephone services in the US.
The job cuts, out of a total of 96,500, are intended to save the company
Dollars 900m a year, shoring up the profitability of its long-distance
services.
Although AT&amp;T's call volumes rose by 5 per cent last year, its telephone
services revenue grew by less than 1 per cent, to Dollars 39.9bn. This was
due to the increased use of discounts and special promotions to attract
business, the company said. US long-distance rivals MCI and Sprint recorded
revenue increases of 13 per cent and 7 per cent respectively last year.
Some 8,000 managers will lose their jobs in the cuts, which will take place
over the next two years. Most individuals to go will be notified by the end
of March.
AT&amp;T said the costs of the job cuts were covered by a Dollars 1.3bn charge
included in its results for the last quarter of 1993.
In addition to the job cuts announced yesterday, around 3,500 telephone
operators are to lose their jobs by the end of this year under plans
announced previously.
Despite the low revenue growth, AT&amp;T improved its profit margin from
telephone services last year by two percentage points, to 38 per cent, as it
cut costs by Dollars 550m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
