<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / BP defies price fall to return to profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Petroleum fought off the effects of falling oil prices to announce a
return to the black as it reaped the rewards of a wide-ranging restructuring
and disposal programme.
Pre-tax profits last year on a replacement cost basis - which excludes the
effects of changes in inventory values - were Pounds 896m after exceptional
items, against losses of Pounds 352m for 1992. Exceptional items for the
year totalled Pounds 240m. BP saw a 56 per cent improvement in comparable
fourth quarter profits to Pounds 315m.
The group also substantially improved its cash flow, recording a positive
contribution of Pounds 1.95bn before financing, against a Pounds 607m
outflow in 1992.
This was partly due to the success of BP's disposal programme which has
raised more than Pounds 3bn since 1992.
Mr David Simon, chief executive, said the group had 'really been tested. We
have shown a steady improvement in our financial performance in spite of the
oil price.'
Average oil prices declined during the year by more than Dollars 2 to about
Dollars 16 a barrel. Since early December they have fallen to about Dollars
13.50, but Mr Simon said BP's larger oil fields had remained profitable. He
did not hold great hope for a revival of oil prices in the near future and
said BP would have to 'find a way to live in a Dollars 13 to Dollars 14
world'. This would mean greater efforts to maintain margins, rather than
relying on the oil price for profits. The group announced it intends to find
a further Dollars 1bn (Pounds 600m) savings in the next three years, but
there were no firm plans for further redundancies. There was room for
cutting variable costs, Mr Simon said.
The main exploration and production business returned operating profits of
Pounds 1.9bn, against Pounds 1.7bn last year. Mr Simon said this had been
achieved through margin management and increased gas production, as well as
cost-cutting.
Refining and marketing jumped from Pounds 304m to Pounds 810m. The
improvement largely resulted from Pounds 265m of cost reductions.
The chemicals division was hit by low petrochemical prices and incurred
losses of Pounds 68m, against a Pounds 24m deficit last year.
The fourth quarter dividend was 2.1p (against 2.1p), for a total of 8.4p
(against 10.5p). Earnings per share on a replacement cost basis, before
exceptionals rose from 9.9p to 10.7p.
Lex, Page 18; Background, Page 21
