<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Unit trust industry set to demand single pricing: Threat of
international competition prompts proposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The unit trust industry is set to call for radical change to the way unit
trusts are priced in order to meet the threat of increasing international
competition.
In spite of record Pounds 9.1bn unit trust sales last year, the industry
believes the existing 'dual pricing' system, under which investors buy units
at an 'offer' price and sell at a lower 'bid' price, is a barrier to its
performance, especially outside the UK.
It hopes that 'single pricing' will make unit trusts easier for UK investors
to understand and more accessible to customers in US and European markets.
A draft paper from the Association of Unit Trusts and Investment Funds calls
on the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief regulator, to
introduce rules for the single pricing of trusts on the basis of a
'mid-price' valuation.
Demand for change has intensified following the Treasury's announcement late
last year that single pricing would be used for the open-ended investment
company (OEIC), a form of pooled investment which will be introduced into
the UK, perhaps as early as next year. The OEIC is already common in other
European countries and in North America.
Many believe it could be very damaging for the unit trust industry if this
single-priced investment product became available while trusts continued to
use the dual pricing system.
The AUTIF paper has yet to be finalised. However, it is the result of
extensive consultation among association members, who make up about 90 per
cent of fund managers, and is unlikely to change substantively.
Standard Life, which makes up most of the other 10 per cent, agrees with the
call for single pricing.
The paper comes in response to the SIB's consultation document in October
last year on ways of deregulating the Pounds 84bn unit trust industry. The
SIB said that given the lack of consensus in the industry at the time it
would not impose single-pricing.
The AUTIF response seeks to take account of concern that the move to a
single pricing system could lead to extra costs being borne by the fund
itself and prove unfair to those who continue to hold units.
Under the existing system, the difference between the bid and offer prices
reflects the fund's charges and costs.
With single pricing there is a risk of 'diluting' the fund because, by using
a mid-price, the whole cost of a particular transaction would not be met by
each buyer or seller but would fall partly on the fund itself.
The association suggests that fund managers who want to reduce dilution
should be allowed to make separate payments into the fund, perhaps from
their own charges or from an entry or exit charge.
Any such charge would have to be disclosed in advance to the potential
investor.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COSTS  Product costs &amp; Product prices.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
