<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: BT
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BT's third-quarter profits show that the cash generator continues to purr
away. What is perhaps more interesting is the way in which the marketing
battle is hotting up between BT, Mercury and the other new competitors. The
RPI-7.5 per cent price cap which BT now endures means substantial price
cuts. BT seems to have decided to turn necessity into virtue by making price
cut a marketing weapon. This week's abolition of peak rate tariffs is aimed
at business users. But the weekend low rates and 'family and friends'
promotion is aimed at domestic users, implying that Mercury and the cable
television companies are having some impact.
The fight will intensify as new services and products are launched, and next
year BT must come up with further price initiatives. Cable television, which
has plumbed in its own lines, has substantial flexibility over how it
structures its marketing push. Mercury, by contrast, operates primarily
through BT's own system and pays for this through a price structure which
mirrors the retail tariffs. That makes it difficult to offer radically
different options, such as free evening calls. Mercury is legally
challenging that structure. If it succeeds, marketing expertise is going to
change the nature of the retail telecoms battle.
</TEXT>
