<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Colour photocopiers adapted for
textiles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the US colour photocopying is being adapted to replace traditional
silk-screening to print images on everything from T-shirts to boxer shorts.
The Xerox Digital Textile Imaging service (XDTI) feeds images - generated on
a PC screen or from any paper source - through a Xerox copier and prints
them on to special transfer paper. The paper copy is then sent to the XDTI
production centre near Seattle, where the images are heat-transferred on to
the textile items.
The printed image has a resolution of 400 dots-per-inch, compared with an
average of 80 dots-per-inch for silk screen printing. It also eliminates the
need for multiple screens and inks. Xerox: US, 716 423 5090.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
