<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Cost of training turns Wayne's world on its head
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wayne Law spent years as a builder but always wanted to be a hairdresser.
Last year he decided to stop waiting - so wound up his business and sold his
home.
That, he decided, was the quickest way to gain a qualification. Joining a
government-financed training course would have meant waiting six months. If
he had accepted unemployment benefit he would have have been barred from a
full-time course because the unemployed are expected to be available for
work.
By selling his home and moving to rented accommodation Mr Law was able to
finance the Pounds 4,700 cost of a nine-month course at a private training
centre in London. 'I wanted to take control of my own life,' said
34-year-old Mr Law. 'I am not the sort of person to take unemployment
benefit and just sit back.'
He is one of a growing number of people prepared to take drastic action to
secure qualifications. Keith Bulmer is still employed as a painter and
decorator, but spends most of his time off in college. Every Thursday he
joins a small huddle of students swapping notes at Newham Community College
in east London.
They are the people who might have missed the previous week's session or
were only able to reach the day-long course after completing shift work.
Several of the course's participants are working full-time like Mr Bulmer
and paying for their training in their own time - because their employers
have declined to pay, in spite of doing so in the past.
Mr Bulmer and his three friends on the course all work for Newham council.
Their employer paid for two years part-time study for the Ordinary National
Certificate (ONC) in building studies, but declined last September to fund
the higher qualification.
'The council did not give us a reason for not giving us time off,' said Mr
Bulmer, 28. 'I guess they cannot afford it or else they fear we will try and
get new jobs when we have better skills.'
Local authorities are among many employers who have cut back on part-time
further education courses. The Association of Metropolitan Authorities said:
'There has been a significant cut-back in training and development budgets
in local authorities - particularly metropolitan authorities who have had to
make big cuts in their budgets. Priorities are having to be set.'
For those unable to finance themselves the government provides Career
Development Loans. Established in 1988, the scheme, backed by three banks,
provides interest-free loans of up to Pounds 5,000, which will increase to a
maximum of Pounds 8,000 next year. The loan is interest free for the period
of training and one subsequent month. This is to be raised shortly to six
months.
In 1992-93, 10,000 people took up the loans. 12,500 are forecast to do so in
1993-94 and 20,000 the following year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
