<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Fall in employer-funded education worries CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry and education organisations said
yesterday they were disappointed at figures which showed that employers have
cut sharply the number of workers they send on further education courses.
The figures came at the same time as others which showed that employees who
want extra training were resorting to paying for classes themselves, and
were often using holiday time to attend them.
The Department of Employment is to work with the Further Education Training
Council, which supplied the figures, to try to explain why employers are not
taking up part-time training places.
The number of part-time students funded by employers has fallen by 7 per
cent - in spite of new financial incentives to do so.
The Confederation of British Industry said it was unhappy with the figures -
but suggested that the decline in employer take-up would prove 'transient'.
Many recruits were staying longer in education and did not attend
day-release schemes when they started work, while the recession had hit
overall recruitment and so the numbers of employees being sent on training
courses.
The Association for Colleges described the take-up from employers as
'disappointing'.
The number of part-time day students funding themselves has risen 16 per
cent in the 1993-94 academic year - more than twice the government target.
Further education colleges were removed from local authority control and
became independent institutions in April last year. Funding council figures
show that the number of full-time students has since increased by 8 per
cent.
But the overall rise in numbers was restricted to 5.1 per cent compared with
a government target of 6.9 per cent. Numbers taking evening classes also
dropped.
Greater London saw the sharpest increase in further education take-up at 9.3
per cent while in East Anglia the increase was only 3.0 per cent.
Employer-led participation dropped 12.9 per cent in Yorkshire and
Humberside, but rose by 4.6 per cent in London.
Mr Tim Boswell, further-education minister, said the overall expansion had
'confounded the doom and gloom merchants', but added that colleges should
make clear to industry that further education could improve business.
</TEXT>
