<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Wider Customs powers attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour protested yesterday at government proposals to extend Customs
officials' powers of inspection and complained that a planned two-stage
review procedure would not allow companies a fair chance of appeal against
Customs &amp; Excise decisions, Graham Bowley writes.
New proposals in the finance bill would give Customs officials the power to
inspect the books of companies that 'finance or facilitate' businesses
involved in import and export activities.
Mr Andrew Smith, a Labour treasury spokesman, said: 'Banks, lawyers and
accountants would certainly come within this definition. Customs would now
have the right to demand these people breach client confidentiality.'
But Sir John Cope, the paymaster general, said that the move away from the
physical control of goods as they passed the borders towards an audit-based
system in the collection of Customs duties meant that such powers were
necessary to give auditors access to the information they required.
He said such measures already existed for the collection of excise duties
and VAT.
