<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Roof bolts cleared in mine fall probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bilsthorpe Colliery accident last August in which three miners were
killed was not caused by any defect in its roof-bolting system, according to
a report into the accident published yesterday by the Health and Safety
Executive.
The roof fall at the Nottinghamshire site occurred in a roadway being driven
through coal close to an exhausted area. This practice is known in the
industry as 'skin-to-skin' working.
The report said the roof fall was caused by rock movement 'probably'
triggered by 'the relatively high rate of advance of the working in the
roadway'. It recommends stopping 'skin-to-skin' working.
It exonerates the use of roof-bolts at Bilsthorpe, even suggesting their
presence may have helped men to escape from the rock fall.
Mr John Rimington, HSE director-general, said the accident had 'not been
reasonably foreseeable'.
The Health and Safety Commission welcomed the report but added that it was
appointing Sir Bernard Crossland of Queen's University, Belfast, to 'hear
publicly, any new or further views or evidence that may exist'. The
commission will wait for that report before considering further action.
British Coal welcomed the report's findings and said it was already
implementing its recommendations.
'For many years BC has driven similar roadways as that at Bilsthorpe,
particularly in the midlands, without major incident,' said a spokesman.
'All such developments have now been stopped'.
</TEXT>
