<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Solicitor breaks the Bar's monopoly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bar's 200-year monopoly on advocacy in the higher courts formally came
to an end yesterday when Mr Richard Slowe, a former barrister, became the
first solicitor to exercise advocacy rights in the High Court, Robert Rice
writes.
Mr Slowe, a partner of City solicitors S J Berwin, appeared before Mr
Justice Ferris in the Chancery Division of the High Court as junior to Mr
Alan Steinfeld QC in a business expansion scheme case.
He was one of 32 solicitors whose applications for exemption from the
requirement to take an advocacy training course before gaining higher court
advocacy rights was granted by the society yesterday.
All 32 have either experience of work in the higher courts as part-time
judges, or have formerly practised as barristers.
Three solicitors were granted audience rights for civil cases only, 16 for
criminal cases only and 13 for both civil and criminal cases.
Mr Walter Merricks, the society's assistant secretary general, said he was
delighted that 'at long last some solicitors will be able to represent their
clients in the higher courts'.
More than 1,000 solicitors had enquired about obtaining rights of audience
in the higher courts since the profession got the go-ahead from the Lord
Chancellor and the four senior judges last December.
</TEXT>
