<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Councils unite to save steel industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A coalition of 24 Tory and Labour-controlled councils will be launched in
the Northamptonshire steel town of Corby today to fight for the survival of
the country's steel industry.
The campaign, to be called SteelAction, will also demand more action from
the government to end subsidies paid to rival foreign industries by their
governments.
The councils, which all have steelworks in their areas, claim that more than
50,000 jobs are at risk - this is more than the number of jobs lost recently
in the coal industry.
Mr Roger Stone, a Rotherham councillor is to be the chair of SteelAction. He
said: 'We have seen one industry after another disappear from Britain, and
we're uniting now to stop the steel industry collapsing in the same way.'
SteelAction Organisers say that the country's steel industry faces pressure
on two fronts. Subsidies paid to competitors in Italy, Spain and Germany put
them at a grave disadvantage, while the continuing over-capacity on the
continental mainland badly affects what is left of the UK industry.
Mr Stone said that the government either had to force the countries still
paying subsidies to stop the payments and to make capacity cuts or it should
give UK producers temporary financial help so that they can survive.
The launch of the coalition comes on the eve of a meeting of Eurofer, which
groups the big European steelmakers, to discuss the industry's restructuring
plans.
Non-aided private companies are holding back from offering capacity until
the European Union takes a tougher line on subsidies.
</TEXT>
