FT  11 FEB 94 / Employees of BNF given vote go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employees of British Nuclear Fuels who are also members of Copeland borough
council have been given dispensation by the Department of the Environment to
vote in committees on matters relating to BNF's business.
Last month the council was advised by a QC specialising in local government
law that councillors should not vote on planning applications by their
employer or their spouses' employer.
Nine Copeland councillors who are BNF employees at its Sellafield nuclear
processing plant, and another three whose spouses work for BNF, sought
dispensation. The department has ruled that, provided they declare an
interest, the 12 can vote in committees on applications by BNF or UK Nirex,
the nuclear industry's waste disposal body.
But they are not allowed to vote on these applications at full council
meetings, although they may speak.
