<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Engineering employers seek fresh link with CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Engineering Employers' Federation is making a fresh attempt to cement
ties with the Confederation of British Industry following the scrapping of
their plan to merge central activities.
Mr Graham Mackenzie, the federation's president and acting director-general,
said yesterday that it is looking at a 'close alliance' with the CBI on
areas where they overlap.
It is focusing on overlaps with the CBI's National Manufacturing Council on
issues such as manufacturing representation and policy, and European Union
matters.
Mr Mackenzie said he would be presenting a paper to the federation's council
next week, on entering into a memorandum of understanding with the CBI. This
would draw the EEF into a joint programme of alliance with the council.
The proposal is designed to avoid the same obstacles that tripped up the
original merger plan. The EEF's 14 regional associations opposed the deal
because of worries that the services they receive may no longer be suitable
for engineer-ing companies if the EEF's central functions were merged with
the CBI or the council.
But Mr Mackenzie stressed that the associations would retain their autonomy,
and that the federation would keep control of the services it offers.
The uncertainty over the future of the EEF has delayed the search for a new
director-general since the abrupt resignation of Mr Neil Johnson in the
autumn. However, Mr Mackenzie said the federation was 'here to stay' and
within the past two weeks it had begun searching for a replace-ment.
If Mr Mackenzie's proposal is approved next week, details will then be
worked out. Meanwhile the federation has set up an internal working party to
discuss other areas of potential co-operation with the CBI such as
employment policy.
</TEXT>
