FT  11 FEB 94 / Gould renews attack on Smith
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bryan Gould yesterday renewed his attack on Mr John Smith's leadership of
the Labour party within a day of announcing he was quitting politics to
return to his native New Zealand, David Owen writes.
The former shadow cabinet member, who was once a candidate for the party
leadership, argued that Labour bore a share of the blame for the recent
recession. Launching a pamphlet calling for a more radical approach to
economic policy, he urged Labour to 'stop giving the Tories a free run' and
to 'make the case for a new and real commitment to full employment'.
In a document that he agreed was his 'swansong', Mr Gould urged Labour to
adopt a 22-point policy checklist. This included identifying full
employment, not stable prices, as the central aim of monetary policy,
reducing interest rates by between 2 and 3 percentage points and increasing
taxes on the 'very rich'.
His attack was immediately pounced on by Mr Gerry Malone, the Conservative
deputy chairman, who said Mr Gould was leaving Labour 'disillusioned by John
Smith's timid leadership'.
