<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Continued recovery predicted for engineering output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Engineering output will continue to recover after declining at the end of
last year, the Engineering Employers' Federation predicted yesterday, but it
warned against a deteriorating trade balance, Graham Bowley writes.
In an interim update to the federation's half-yearly Engineering Economics
Trends report, Mr Ian Thompson, federation economic adviser, said that the
recovery was being led by the electronics and vehicle sectors.
Engineering output declined in the second half of last year, but the
federation now expects positive growth for all major sectors except
aerospace. Output from the aerospace equipment sector will continue to
decline. But 'the trade deficit could be an inhibiting factor on the UK
economy,' he said.
The federation said the most interesting picture to emerge is a large shift
in the pattern of UK exports and imports from European to non-EU trading
partners.
Engineering employment will continue to fall during this year, said Mr
Thompson, but he emphasised that this is not necessarily a bad thing as
companies improve on efficiency.
Referring to the planned tax rises he said: 'The impact of the tax increase
has been exaggerated and will not stop the recovery.'
