<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Pay frozen for biggest council's 104,000 staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strathclyde, Britain's largest council, said yesterday that its 104,000
staff will receive no pay increase this year and blamed the government's
capping of its budget.
Local government leaders fear that other councils may also find it difficult
to meet pay rises of 2 per cent to 3 per cent - while conforming to the
government's policy of a freeze on public-sector pay bills - because of
budget constraints.
Mr Robert Gould, Labour leader of the council which includes Glasgow, said:
'Strathclyde just cannot afford to include pay increases in the council
budget this year. It is deplorable that the government have placed us in
this difficult position.'
Strathclyde's final budget and the size of its regional council tax for the
1994-1995 financial year will be fixed at a special meeting of the council
scheduled for March 9. But council leaders said yesterday their budget had
been set tightly by Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, at Pounds 1.9bn.
Every 1 percentage point pay rise would cost the regional council more than
Pounds 3m.
Councillors say the government's 1994-1995 grant settlement for Strathclyde
takes no account of any pay awards for the staff.
Mr Gould said: 'We are worried that (the pay freeze) will lower staff morale
at a very critical time for local government. Strathclyde remains committed
to honouring nationally negotiated pay settlements and we will do everything
we can to press the government to provide the necessary resources.'
The council's policy and resources committee is demanding that Mr Lang meet
local authorities to reconsider what it sees as his failure to include an
element for pay within the 1994-1995 grant settlement.
Unison, the main public services union, reacted angrily last night to
Strathclyde's announcement. Mr Mark Irvine, the union's local government
head in Scotland, said: 'The proposed pay freeze is completely unacceptable.
We will be seeking an urgent meeting with the secretary of state for
Scotland to discuss the financial crisis facing local government in
Scotland.'
The union said it understood the financial difficulties facing Strathclyde
and other councils in Scotland but warned that it could not accept that
low-paid local government workers should receive no pay rise at all in 1994.
</TEXT>
