<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Penalties proposed for late payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is proposing to introduce clauses in contracts covering more
than Pounds 5bn of public-sector building work to ensure that construction
companies and their subcontractors are paid on time.
A consultation paper detailing the proposals, published yesterday by the
Department of the Environment, received a mixed response from the building
industry.
At the heart of the proposals are procedures to ensure that payments made by
the customer to the main contractor are passed on to sub-contractors which
do the bulk of the work.
Sub-contractors have complained that main contractors are delaying payments
to improve their own financial position at the expense of specialist
builders.
The environment department is proposing that government building contracts
include clauses requiring subcontractors to be paid within 17 days of
architects issuing payment certificates.
Payment periods for government departments and agencies to pay main
contractors would also be fixed, the department said.
The Specialist Engineering Contractors Group, representing sub-contractors,
welcomed the proposals - but said it was concerned that there was no system
to adjudicate when there was disagreement over the amount to be paid. It
said main contractors often queried prices as a means of delaying payment.
</TEXT>
