<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Fresh bid revealed for Channel 5
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three big media organisations - MAI, Time Warner and Pearson - yesterday
announced that they had formed a consortium to bid for a national Channel 5
television licence if one is advertised.
The consortium would offer national programming and a series of local
services for leading UK cities. It would resemble the US television system
with a national network serving a host of regional affiliates.
MAI is the controlling shareholder in Meridian Broadcasting, the ITV company
for the south of England, and recently made an agreed bid for Anglia
Television. Time Warner is the largest media group in the world and Pearson,
owner of the Financial Times, also owns Thames Television, the ITV company
that lost its franchise to Carlton.
The consortium is the most weighty so far to announce its interest in
Channel 5, which could reach around three-quarters of the UK population.
In December 1992, the Independent Television Commission rejected the only
bid for the Channel 5 licence - put together by Thames (not then owned by
Pearson), Time Warner and Pearson. The ITC did not think the business plan
sufficiently robust and decided that the shareholders were not sufficiently
committed.
For some time, the ITC has been looking to see whether the franchise should
be readvertised or the frequencies reserved to develop a host of digital
television channels in this country.
The ITC will take its decision 'shortly'. The likeliest outcome is that
Channel 5 will be re-advertised, but as part of a co-ordinated plan to
develop digital television gradually.
The ITC has been trying to find ways to reduce the number of video recorders
that would have to be re-tuned for Channel 5 to go ahead. Extensive
re-tuning because of the interference that would be caused by the Channel 5
signal was one of the problems with the original proposal.
Lord Hollick, chief executive of MAI, said yesterday: 'This is a golden
opportunity to bring in a new distinctive channel offering both national and
city-based programmes.'
It would offer extra choice at no cost to viewers and extra choice for
advertisers, particularly local advertisers, he added.
At the moment Pearson, as a company owning a national newspaper and an
independent television production company, could only take a 5 per cent
stake.
The government has, however, announced a review of cross-media ownership
rules.
</TEXT>
