<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / TAP air crews to work 35% longer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TAP-Air Portugal, the loss-making state airline, said yesterday it had
reached an agreement with its flight crew on a 35 per cent rise in working
time, writes Peter Wise in Lisbon. Mr Jose Braz, president of the flight
attendants' union, said they had agreed to increase their maximum flying
time from 550 to 750 hours a year in return for enhanced benefits.
The government hailed the accord as a breakthrough for its plans to return
the debt-ridden company to profit by injecting Es180bn (Pounds 690m) in
fresh capital.
Pilots have already accepted the increase in flying time. However, a TAP
statement that the flight crew had also agreed to a pay freeze for this year
was disputed by the union. Mr Braz said it was still pressing for a 7 per
cent increase.
According to a TAP spokesman, the union signed an agreement accepting
whatever pay rises were decided for the whole company between 1994 and 1997.
'We have already made clear there will be no increases for anyone in 1994
and the union has clearly accepted that.'
</TEXT>
