<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 94 / Electricity generators to escape monopolies reference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity industry's regulator, is
today expected to announce that National Power and PowerGen, the UK's two
largest power generators, will not be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
The move will clear the way for the government to sell its 40 per cent stake
in the companies later this year, probably in July or October, and realise
at least Pounds 4bn of the Pounds 5.5bn target it is aiming to raise from
privatisation receipts in the next financial year.
The sum the government will raise may grow significantly in the next few
months as the two companies' share prices have been held back by fears of a
possible reference.
Shares in both companies, and in the entire electricity sector, were down
yesterday amid market uncertainty over Prof Littlechild's announcement
today. PowerGen fell 17p to 525p and National Power 12p to 461p.
However, in a statement of more than 20 pages, Prof Littlechild will say
that both National Power and PowerGen 'have agreed to give undertakings such
that a reference is not required'.
It is thought that the generators have agreed with the regulator that prices
in the electricity pool - through which suppliers like the regional
electricity companies buy their power supplies - should not rise above a
certain level.
The most likely cap is for two years at between 2.4p and 2.55p per kilowatt
hour, about 7 per cent below levels in the first half of the 1994-95 year.
Today's statement is also likely to include reference to the possibility of
generators selling some of their power stations to other companies.
Immediate disposals are unlikely, however.
Prof Littlechild promised last July to make an early decision on a reference
after a sharp rise in pool prices. He has missed two deadlines to make a
decision, promised at first for 1993 and then for mid-January this year.
The generators play a crucial role in the determination of pool prices. They
bid a series of prices for each of their power stations for every half hour
of the day. The main determinant of prices is the price of the most
expensive plant needed to supply electricity throughout the country in any
half hour period.
Critics of the pool system say it gives the generators too much power and
that the generators effectively operate a duopoly. However, few critics
supported a reference, which they believe would affect the whole electricity
supply industry.
Prof Littlechild has been keen to see the generators selling some of their
power stations since this would increase competition and, he believes,
reduce prices.
London stocks, Page 40
</TEXT>
