<DATE>940210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Glaxo declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nervousness crept into Glaxo shares on findings from a US health panel that
could be damaging to Zantac, Glaxo's anti-ulcer drug and biggest selling
treatment.
Zantac works by blocking acid formation and the health panel tentatively
concluded that some patients should be treated with antibiotics as well as
acid-blocking drugs. The news saw Glaxo shares decline 10 to 662p in spite
of the potentially beneficial effect of a stronger dollar and the launch of
a big call warrant by BZW on leading pharmaceuticals stocks. Dealers said a
US press conference, scheduled to take place after the London market closed,
could hit the stock again today.
SmithKline Beecham, which also has an ulcer treatment, Tagamet, but also
represents part of the BZW warrant, firmed a penny in the 'A's to 418p.
Tagamet comes off patent in May and analysts said the potential loss of
revenue was already in the share price.
Buying ahead of figures today saw BP improve 5 1/2 to 390 1/2 p on one of
the heaviest turnovers in the FT-SE 100 Index - 13m shares. The stock
ignored the effect of a weaker oil price and responded instead to a stronger
US currency and a smattering of pre-results recommendations.
The range of forecasts is enormous, with analysts looking for historic net
income of between Pounds 670m and Pounds 1bn and replacement cost profits of
between Pounds 757m and Pounds 1.1bn. However, Credit Lyonnais Laing was
confidently predicting that the share price would hit 500p by the end of the
year, while James Capel, Lehman Brothers and NatWest Securities were also
continuing to offer support.
Aero-engine manufacturer Rolls-Royce moved strongly against a weak market
trend as speculation that it is to merge with its US rival Pratt &amp; Whitney
returned.
The shares gained 8 at 183p in average trade of 4.7m. The talk about a
merger between the two groups first surfaced at the end of last year, but
then faded. However, one analyst dismissed yesterday's rumours, saying: 'I
cannot rule it out, but the rationalisation costs for the two rival engine
programmes would be very high indeed.'
Consideration of results from Lloyds Abbey Life saw its share price slip 15
to 447p. Analysts said the headline figure of Pounds 323.6m was in line with
expectations but the group, which is the insurance arm of Lloyds Bank, had
not included any provisions for the mis-selling of pensions. Mr Roger Harvey
of Kleinwort Benson reduced his 1994 forecast for Lloyds Abbey by Pounds 23m
to Pounds 359m. Lloyds Bank, which reports tomorrow, advanced 7 to 613p.
Analysts are looking for profits of up to Pounds 1.05bn, compared with
Pounds 801m previously.
Leading bank stocks fell sharply in early trading in response to weaker
gilts prices. However, most recovered by the close, with two-way business
prompting very heavy turnover. Barclays ended 2 lower at 587p on turnover of
13m and NatWest 3 off at 539p, also with 13m traded.
In a weak telecoms sector, Cable and Wireless attracted attention as BZW
issued a buy recommendation, arguing that the company's investment in
Australian telecoms group Optus was now worth an estimated Pounds 500m.
The broker reckons that Optus has snatched a 10 per cent share of the
Australian long distance market in only its second year of business.
Together with its other telecoms operations, BZW calaculates Optus's value
at Pounds 2bn. C&amp;W has a 24.5 per cent stake in the venture and could reap
further dividends should it be floated, a prospect deemed likely in the
medium term. Turnover in C&amp;W hit a busy 7m, but the shares fell after an
initial gain, losing 9 at 509p.
Holiday operator Owners Abroad was the star performer of an otherwise
lacklustre leisure sector as it delivered satisfactory results and an upbeat
trading statement. The shares shot forward, closing 20 ahead at 120p on
turnover of 6m.
Mr Bruce Jones of Smith New Court said the company's claim of a 15 per cent
market share demonstrated its renewed competitiveness and there was relief
that the results contained no nasty surprises. He added: 'Owners are now on
the same rating as Airtours, but if Owners get it right there is more upside
potential.' Airtours shares added 2 at 586p.
A domestic court case over the issue of tied pubs and a downbeat
presentation from Vaux were said to have combined to depress drinks stocks.
Vaux slipped 8 to 288p. Kleinwort Benson used the opportunity to reiterate
its negative stance on the stock.
Wilton Group saw very heavy two-way business after news that the group is to
team up with Shaw Media Corporation to launch a Chinese-language satellite
channel in Europe. The shares held at 3 3/4 p with 36m traded.
Profit forecast upgrades following well-received figures on Tuesday helped
Reuters Holdings climb 47 to 2018p.
Marks and Spencer, muted in recent sessions on rumours of flagging sales,
stabilised and closed 1 1/2 firmer at 427p.
Financial software concern Coda Group made a successful market debut, the
shares coming to the market at 235p and closing yesterday at 265p.
Property stocks were weak, although Hammerson moved forward 3 to 422p on
talk of an imminent deal.
</TEXT>
