<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The derivatives sector had a volatile session which saw a recovery on the
back of a firm Wall Street following initial weakness due to weakness in
gilts, writes Joel Kibazo.
In stock index futures, the March contract on the FT-SE 100 opened at a
discount to an already weak cash market at 3,420. The poor form of the gilts
sector prompted selling from the large institutions and the contract fell
through its recent support level of 3,400.
However traders reported buying at the lower levels, even as March declined
indicating there was no clear view on the direction of trading from market
participants during the morning.
The strength of US bonds boosted the New York market and helped March
bounce, which also offered dealers much sought after arbitrage
opportunities. March finished at 3,430, at a 6 point premium to cash. Volume
was 18,061 at the official close.
Index options continued to lead the way in traded options business. The
FT-SE 100 option finished with 20,842 lots while the Euro FT-SE 100 traded
3,541 contracts. BP was the busiest stock option at 3,561 lots, closely
followed by NatWest Bank with 2,341 lots and Hanson with 1,940 lots.
Activity in the OMLX futures remained poor with volume falling to 449 lots
as the March contract on the Mid 250 index closed at 4,101.
</TEXT>
