<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / International Capital Markets: Russia opens T-bill market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russia is to open its domestic Treasury bill market to foreign investors,
allowing non-residents to take up to 10 per cent of the next bond issue on
February 15, Reuter reports from Moscow. The finance ministry said it would
put up Rbs100bn of three-month Treasury bills at this month's auction.
Russia's tiny small Treasury bill market has been restricted to domestic
players. Turnover, about Rbs2.2bn a day over the past week, has fallen
sharply as investors moved their assets into hard currency because of doubts
about government economic policies. This year the rouble has fallen 25 per
cent against the dollar.
Russian Treasury bills yield more than 230 per cent, up from about 185 per
cent at the January auction.
Western emerging market portfolio managers have begun looking at investment
opportunities in Russia's new financial markets. Treasury bills offer one
possibility.
Foreign banks are interested in finance ministry bonds, issued last year to
compensate domestic companies whose funds were frozen by the foreign trade
bank of the former Soviet Union at the start of 1992.
</TEXT>
